Taiwan is becoming a bigger issue between the world's two biggest superpowers. Taipei — a U.S. ally — and Beijing have avoided war for more than seven decades, but that balance is getting harder to maintain as China becomes more assertive in its desire for reunification.

Watch the full video at the link in bio to understand why analysts say Taiwan's status is "the most likely issue to draw China and the U.S. into a direct military conflict."

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 20, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Trump ally Tom Barrack is arrested on foreign agent charges Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Tom Barrack Jr., the founder of Colony Capital and inaugural chair to Donald Trump, was arrested on charges of acting as an unregistered agent of a foreign government, the United Arab Emirates.

Barrack was arrested in California on Tuesday, according to a Justice Department statement.

Others tied to Trump have been charged with violations of the Foreign Agents Registration Act. Among them are former top fundraiser Elliott Broidy, former Trump campaign chairman Paul Manafort and former national security adviser Michael Flynn.

Link in our bio for this developing story.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 20, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Why junior bankers need 72- hour weeks, according to a senior JPMorgan exec Bloomberg Wealth'.

node.text:
There's a reason Wall Street bankers start out working 12-hour days, six days a week, says the CEO of JPMorgan’s asset and wealth management business: they're learning on the job.

Mary Erdoes, whose unit manages around $4 trillion, says the intense level of training helps them gain the necessary skills in two to three years. "If you think 10,000 hours is about what you need to master any subject, if someone comes in and has a regular, eight-hour-a-day job, five days a week, it's gonna take about five years to have a base-level mastery," she told David Rubenstein on Bloomberg TV.

Wall Street's grueling hours — albeit with base pay topping $100,000 — have gotten something of a re-evaluation during the pandemic. Read more at the link in bio.

node.text:
The future of Earth is in outer space, says Jeff Bezos. 

After an “awe-inspiring” trip to outer space on the Blue Origin rocket, Bezos says he’s doubling down on building the infrastructure to move heavy industry off Earth and into the stars to protect our “fragile” atmosphere.

Watch the first interview with the billionaire founder of Amazon after he landed in our link in bio.

node.text:
Amazon's billionaire founder Jeff Bezos and three others landed safely after Blue Origin's first crewed flight — a key milestone in the quest to make space tourism a reality.
 
The company's New Shepard rocket reached an altitude of about 62 miles during the 10 minute flight, giving its passengers a few moments of weightlessness and a view of the Earth down below.

On board were Bezos, his brother, Mark, and the youngest and oldest people to travel to space: Wally Funk, 82, a former astronaut trainee, and Oliver Daemen, the 18-year-old son of a Dutch financier.

The wealthiest person on the planet was heard saying "best day ever" shortly before the capsule landed. He exited wearing a cowboy hat. Full story at the link in bio.

📷: Blue Origin, Joe Raedle/Getty Images

node.text:
Someday, the post-pandemic equities rally is going to end. When it does it will take a lot of newly christened stock bulls with it.

Retail investors' refusal to bend has been the signature fact of the stock market for at least 12 months. In 2021 alone, their appetite for dip-buying has put a floor under four other selloffs that look much like the one that sheared almost 3% off the S&P 500 Index since Thursday.
 
Whether their devotion is enough to turn the tide again is the biggest question in markets right now. Read more at the link in our bio.

node.text:
All around Wall Street, junior bankers are quitting or face burnout. Banks are trying to turn the tide with raises, bonuses, vacations and even free Pelotons, all representing a silent plea: Please don’t quit.

All that means it’s never been more lucrative to be a young banker in the U.S. The problem, though, is that it’s also never been more lucrative for aspirants to work outside the gilded world of finance — and bank analysts’ grueling workloads have remained, and in some cases gotten worse. Read more at the link in bio.

📷: Spencer Platt/Getty Images

node.text:
Investment strategists are starting to consider a new bearish scenario: the economy has already hit its peak.

Investors had earlier delighted in the prospect of a strong worldwide economic rebound fueled by easy money and vaccine rollouts. But with the ferocious spread of the delta variant and central banks already talking about tighter monetary policy to bring inflation under control, there’s a sense of worry that financial markets have become too optimistic. 

With global equities teetering at all-time highs, there’s no room for error. Read more at the link in bio.

node.text:
On the day of one of the cryptocurrency market’s worst routs, Alex Holland woke up to a wave of messages from friends and family. They knew he had made a big wager recently that prices would fall.

But when he went to check his account on online exchange Binance, he saw that the value of his leveraged bet against Ethereum was sinking rather than reaping huge gains. “I thought it was just a bug and they’d be fixing it,” he says.

By the end of May 19, Ethereum would plummet roughly 20% and Holland’s so-called down token tumbled about 85%. The value was so low it appeared as zero on price charts.

Leveraged tokens are pitched by crypto exchanges as an easy way for amateurs to make outsized bets. In a way, it’s a cautionary tale as old as Wall Street — retail speculators burned by byzantine derivatives — amplified by a lack of regulation, creaky market plumbing, and the extreme volatility of the $1.3 trillion crypto world. Find out more at the link in bio.

📷: A man attends the Bitcoin 2021 Convention in Miami, Florida. By Marco Bello/AFP via Getty Images

node.text:
“Space, the final frontier,” Jeff Bezos said in his high school valedictorian speech. “Meet me there.” On Tuesday, the billionaire will at last get his chance.

The New Shepard spacecraft is scheduled to lift vertically off the desert floor at his ranch in West Texas, travel 62 miles overhead and then detach a crew capsule in which Bezos, his brother, and two passengers will enjoy about three minutes of weightlessness.

A successful launch will represent a delayed triumph of sorts for Bezos and his private space company, Blue Origin. Over the years, the New Shepard program has suffered setbacks and required such significant capital that insiders doubt it will ever be profitable.

But for Amazon’s founder, who has harbored a lifelong dream of opening the space frontier, that may no longer be the goal. Find out more at the link in bio.
